{"answer":"In Macaulay2, a **function closure** is a construct that allows functions to capture and remember the environment in which they were created, retaining access to their local variables even after their execution context has changed. This is particularly useful for creating functions that can use variables defined outside of their own scope. Function closures are a powerful feature that enhances the encapsulation and reusability of functions in programming. In Macaulay2, you can define closures using anonymous functions or by defining a function that returns another function.

You can also have **compiled function closures**, which are optimized versions of standard function closures for performance improvements.

For more detailed information, refer to the class documentation of all function closures and compiled function closures in Macaulay2.","references":["[ov_methods.m2] class of all function closures","[ov_methods.m2] class of all functions","[ov_methods.m2] class of all compiled function closures"]}
